<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_45541693" data-cid="45541693">
    <div id="comment_45541693">
        <header data-points="0" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re:price"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re:price<span> (0)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><span class="author" title="author name and user ID">Anonymous Coward</span> | about 10 months ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=4493645&cid=45541693">(#45541693)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_45541693" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="0" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>Depends greatly on your tablet's screen resolution.</p><p>I bought a couple of China-cheap tablets with a 1024x600 resolution, and then more recently a Nexus 7 with 1920&#195;--1200.</p><p>While I did have eyestrain with the former, the latter's resolution actually seems to give me -less- eyestrain than a physical book, perhaps due to more consistent text-to-background contrast across lighting conditions.</p><p>I would discount any comparison study that didn't explicitly note the resolution of the tablet being tested.</p></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_45541693">
