<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_45541101" data-cid="45541101">
    <div id="comment_45541101">
        <header data-points="5" data-reason="Interesting">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Burn an Ebook?"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Burn an Ebook?<span> (5, Interesting)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~donut1005" class="author" title="author name and user ID">donut1005 (982510) </a> | about 10 months ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=4493645&cid=45541101">(#45541101)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_45541101" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="5" data-reason="Interesting">
            <div class="comment-body">I posed a question on social media recently asking if deleting an Ebook is akin to book burning.  Very few saw a parallel.  Most were appalled at the idea of burning a book but had no problem with deleting an Ebook.  The reason they would not burn a book but were ok with deleting an Ebook?  Not for the preservation of knowledge, not for passing on history, not for any other archeological reason.  Just because they had a sentimental connection via their senses, the touch, the smell.</div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_45541101">
                <div class="comment-footer-controls btn-group btn-group-sm" data-sid="4493645" data-cid="45541101">
