<article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_45541737" data-cid="45541737">
    <div id="comment_45541737">
        <header data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Better to have, not better to read"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Better to have, not better to read<span> (1)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~chispito" class="author" title="author name and user ID">chispito (1870390) </a> | about 10 months ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=4493645&cid=45541737">(#45541737)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_45541737" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body">Yes I like the smell of paper, and the ability to thumb through a book, and the ability to write a personalized note inside when giving one as a gift... but if your primary motivation is getting through content, if the experience of <i>reading</i> books is more important than the experience of <i>having</i> books, ereaders win. They are smaller, and can contain most/all of your collection simultaneously. No more having to choose which book to take on your vacation. Take all of them.</div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_45541737">
